
      After learning that a Brown Thrasher arrived at private property near
the southeast corner of El Centro on 27 December, I chose to look for the
bird myself on 29 December 2016. I arrived at Fig Lagoon at dawn to find
hunters present, so quickly departed and stopped at nearby Sunbeam Lake.
From here I went to the southeast corner of El Centro, but failed to see
the thrasher in over one hour of looking. I then drove north through
Brawley and Westmorland, and looked along the shore of the Salton Sea
between the intersection of Lack and Lindsey Roads and Obsidian Butte, then
spent time around the Salton Sea National Wildlife Refuge HQ and Rock Hill.
As I was departing this area, I received a call advising me that the Brown
Thrasher was present, so I returned to the southeast corner of El Centro
where I remained until 3:30 PM. There was much cloud-cover, but virtually
no wind, and with temperatures ranging from 40 to 65 degrees.
      Heavy rain earlier in the week left most dirt roads with standing
water and muddy, therefore not drivable. Since I spent much time at one
location near El Centro, I made no attempt to estimate numbers of
individuals for most species.
Species seen and/or heard – Snow Goose, Ross’s Goose, Gadwall, American
Wigeon, Mallard, Northern Shoveler, Northern Pintail, Green-winged Teal,
Lesser Scaup, Bufflehead, Common Merganser (2 – two “females” at the north
end of Lack Road were most likely the same two found here on 20 December),
Red-breasted Merganser (6 – six seen scattered along the shore of the
Salton Sea between the intersection of Lack and Lindsey Roads and Rock
Hill), Ruddy Duck, Gambel’s Quail, Pied-billed Grebe, Eared Grebe, Western
Grebe, Neotropic Cormorant (3 – three at Sunbeam Lake early in the
morning), Double-crested Cormorant, American White Pelican, Brown Pelican,
Least Bittern, Great Blue Heron, Great Egret, Snowy Egret, Cattle Egret,
Black-crowned Night-Heron, White-faced Ibis, Turkey Vulture, White-tailed
Kite (1 – one adult at the Salton Sea National Wildlife Refuge HQ),
Northern Harrier, Cooper’s Hawk, Red-tailed Hawk, Ridgway’s Rail, Sora,
Common Gallinule, American Coot, Sandhill Crane (75 – about seventy-five
near the intersection of Keystone and Dogwood Roads between El Centro and
Brawley), Black-necked Stilt, American Avocet, Black-bellied Plover,
Killdeer, Mountain Plover (300 – three-hundred in a dirt field on the east
